      <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
	<p>This edition and translation is based on <ref target="bibl:MNOVH2014">Nakanishi and von Hinüber 2014</ref>. Because it is found on one of the āyāga pillars, which were only added in Phase III of the stūpa’s construction, it probably belongs to the second century CE.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="edition" rend="break-none" xml:lang="pra-Latn">
	<p>
	  <lb n="1"/>
	  <placeName key="pl:Dhānyakaṭaka">dhañakaḍakasa</placeName>
	  <lb n="2"/>
	  ṇaḷabāhukāna<unclear>ṃ</unclear>
	  <lb n="3"/>
	  <persName key="pers:Kan-Utika">utika</persName>putasa
	  <lb n="4"/>
	  gahapatino
	  <lb n="5"/>
	  <persName key="pers:Kan-Asila">asilasa</persName>
	  <lb n="6"/>
	  samātukasa
	  <lb n="7"/>
	  sabhariyasa
	  <lb n="8"/>
	  saputakasa
	  <lb n="9"/>
	  āyuvaḍhanika
	  <lb n="10"/>
	  āyāgathabhā
	  <lb n="11"/>
	  catāri deyadhama
	</p>
      </div>
      <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
	<p>Four columns (decorating) the āyāga(-platform) are the pious gift of the banker <persName key="pers:Kan-Asila">Asila</persName> of the Ṇaḷabāhuka (family) from <placeName key="pl:Dhānyakaṭaka">Dhaññakaṭa</placeName>, the son of <persName key="pers:Kan-Utika">Utika</persName>, together with his mother, with his wife(s), with his son(s) (for the purpose) to prolong (their) life span.
	</p>
      </div>
